===Verb===
{{en-verb|env|i|ed}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To feel displeasure or hatred towards (someone) for their good fortune or possessions. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
# {{context|obsolete|intransitive|lang=en}} To have [[envious]] feelings (at). {{defdate|15th-18th c.}}
#* '''1621''', Robert Burton, ''The Anatomy of Melancholy'', II.3.3:
#*: I do not '''envy''' at their wealth, titles, offices; [...] let me live quiet and at ease.
#: ''Who would '''envy''' at the prosperity of the wicked?'' &mdash; Jeremy Taylor.
# {{context|obsolete|transitive|lang=en}} To give (something) to (someone) [[grudgingly]] or [[reluctantly]]; to [[begrudge]]. {{defdate|16th-18th c.}}
#* '''1590''', Edmund Spenser, ''The Faerie Queene'', III.v:
#*: But that sweet Cordiall, which can restore / A loue-sick hart, she did to him '''enuy''' [...].
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} To show [[malice]] or ill will; to [[rail]].
#: ''He has {{...}} '''envied''' against the people.'' &mdash; Shakespeare.

